bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2542<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/19/02 3:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=80.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Armageddon Can Wait: Stopping Killer Asteroids</span><hr size=1> Hubble just spotted a roaming Black Hole. I posted a reference at Astronomy. You are scaring me Hamster. We should nickname you Nostredamus. 6000 LY. That's a long distance away and nothing to get alarmed about. There are likely plenty of Black Holes closer than 6000 light years. I have long held the belief that people are extremely to reluctant to accept what they cannot see. Plenty of evidence for Black Holes has existed yet they are still doubted. Dust is more common than pebbles. Pebbles more common than Boulders. Boulders more common than Moons. Moons more common than Planets. Planets more common than Stars. It is logical to assume that small proto-stars (unignited) are more common than Stars themselves. Yet it's not seriously accepted because we can't see many of them. Black Holes are more massive than average Stars so we can expect them to be less common and that is what evidence suggests. The mass of a black Hole enables us to detect them with X-ray telescopes. Protostars aren't very massive but probably very common. A wandering Proto-Star would be unstoppable by any technology we could put together in the foreseeable future. If one was heading our way then it would be easier to move the Earth. The only real choice would be evacuation.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 75<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/19/02 10:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=80.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  The black hole gravity whip</span><hr size=1> If we were to gravitationly slingshot a space craft<br>
 past a black hole we could use its gravity to <br>
accelerate a ship to near the velocity of light.<br>
If the black hole were spinning rapidly , this could<br>
prevent its gravitational collapse to infinity, and<br>
thus  give us a transversable wormhole.  There <br>
would be a region of  anti-gravity created by the black holes spinning inside the wormhole in theory<br>
